360","about 1383":"circa 1383","Tilston, Cheshire, England":"Tilston, Cheshire, England","Coole, Cheshire, England":"Hoole, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Catton, Derbyshire, England":"Catton, Derbyshire, England"},"en":{"1364–1385":"1364–1385","1360–Male":"1360–Deceased","1383–1424":"1383–1424","1383–Male":"1383–Deceased","1385–1450":"1385–1450","1387–Male":"1387–Deceased","1424":"1424","1387":"1387","1364":"1364","1385":"1385","1450":"1450","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","about 1383":"about 1383","Tilston, Cheshire, England":"Tilston, Cheshire, England","Coole, Cheshire, England":"Hoole, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Catton, Derbyshire, England":"Catton, Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Peter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Kurt, Otto, Ernst, Fritz, Heinz, Helmut, Horst, Kaspar, Klaus, Siegfried, Wolfgang.","English, Scottish, German, Dutch, French (Alsace and Lorraine), Czech (Moravian), Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian; Hungarian (<b>Péter</b>): from the personal name <i>Peter</i> (Greek <i>Petros</i>, from <i>petra</i> ‘rock’). The personal name was popular throughout Christian Europe in the Middle Ages, having been bestowed by Christ as a byname on the apostle Simon bar Jonah, the brother of Andrew. The name was chosen by Christ for its symbolic significance (John 1:42, Matt. 16:18); Saint Peter is regarded as the founding head of the Christian Church in view of Christ's saying, ‘Thou art Peter and upon this rock I will build my Church’. In Christian Germany in the early Middle Ages this was the most frequent personal name of non-ancient Germanic origin until the 14th century. In North America, this surname has also absorbed cognates from other languages, for example Czech   Petr  , Polish <b>Piotr</b> and <b>Pietr</b>, Albanian <b>Pjetri</b> (from the personal name <i>Pjetër</i>, definite form <i>Pjetri</i>), and also their derivatives (see examples at   Peterson  ). It has also been adopted as a surname by Ashkenazic Jews."],"variants":[{"name":"Mastropietro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carmine, Aldo, Aniello, Antonio, Cesare, Dino, Donato, Marcello, Nicola, Nino, Nunzio.","Italian (southern): from a title of respect composed of <i>mastro</i> ‘master craftsman’ + the personal name <i>Pietro</i>, an equivalent of   Peter  ."]},{"name":"Pecha","meanings":["Czech and Slovak: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Petr</i> (see   Peter  )."]},{"name":"Paetzold","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Armin, Hans, Heinz, Maximilian, Bernd, Dieter, Ernst, Friederike, Heiner, Horst, Markus, Oskar.","German (<b>Pätzold</b>): from the personal name <i>Pätzold</i>, a pet form of   Peter  ."]},{"name":"Patz","meanings":["German (also <b>Pätz</b>): from a pet form of the personal name   Peter   or   Paul  . Compare   Paetz  .","German: from <i>Pazzo</i>, a short form of an ancient Germanic personal name meaning ‘fight’.","East German (of Sorbian origin): topographic name for someone living near a village bake oven, Lower Sorbian <i>pjac</i>."]},{"name":"McFetridge","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Pheadruis</b>, a patronymic from a Gaelic form of the personal name   Peter  . Compare   McPheeters  ."]},{"name":"Petr","meanings":["Czech: from the personal name <i>Petr</i> (see   Peter  )."]},{"name":"Parrill","meanings":["English: from a Middle English personal name, a pet form of   Peter  . Compare   Parrott  ."]},{"name":"Peat","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English and Older Scots personal name <i>Peet</i>, a pet form of   Peter  .","English and Scottish: nickname from Middle English <i>pete</i> ‘peat’, perhaps for someone who cut or sold peat.","Altered form of French   Pitre  ."]},{"name":"Paetz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Juergen.","German (<b>Pätz</b>): from the personal name <i>Pätz</i>, a vernacular form of   Peter  ."]},{"name":"Pech","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos, Jose, Manuel, Alvaro, Diego, Edelmira, Emilio, Francisco, Gilberto, Jorge, Jose Angel.  German Gerhard, Hans, Ilse, Lutz, Manfred, Wolf.","Czech and Slovak; Sorbian (<b>Pěch</b> and <b>P'ech</b>): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Petr</i> (Czech), <i>Pětš</i> (Lower Sorbian), and   Peter   (Slovak). This is also a Germanized form of the Upper Sorbian cognate <b>Pjech</b>.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from Middle High German <i>pech</i> (German <i>Pech</i>) ‘pitch, tar’, presumably a nickname for someone with exceptionally dark skin or hair, or a metonymic occupational name for someone who prepared, sold, or used pitch. This may in part also be the origin of a homonymic Polish, Czech, and Slovak surname (compare above and below)."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Eleanor Peter was born in 1364, in Tilston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 4 sons with William De Horton. She died in 1385, at the age of 21."},"et":{"1364–1385":"1364–1385","1360–Male":"1360–Surnud","1383–1424":"1383–1424","1383–Male":"1383–Surnud","1385–1450":"1385–1450","1387–Male":"1387–Surnud","1424":"1424","1387":"1387","1364":"1364","1385":"1385","1450":"1450","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","about 1383":"umbes 1383","Tilston, Cheshire, England":"Tilston, Cheshire, England","Coole, Cheshire, England":"Hoole, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Catton, Derbyshire, England":"Catton, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"1364–1385":"1364–1385","1360–Male":"1360–Kuollut","1383–1424":"1383–1424","1383–Male":"1383–Kuollut","1385–1450":"1385–1450","1387–Male":"1387–Kuollut","1424":"1424","1387":"1387"